T1  - Factors affecting the foreign banking presence in the U.S.
AU  - Hultman, Charles W.
AU  - Randolph McGee, L.
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 13
IS  - 3
SP  - 383
EP  - 396
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/07/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(89)90049-6
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0378426689900496
AB  - This study examined the determinants of growth in foreign bank participation in U.S. markets over the period 1973–1986. The growing foreign presence in U.S. bank subsidiaries was found to be directly related to changes in direct foreign investment (excluding finance, insurance and real estate) and the exchange value of the dollar, and inversely related to bank price-earnings ratios. The growth of foreign bank branches and agencies in the U.S. was found to be directly related to changes in direct foreign investment (excluding finance, insurance and real estate), the exchange value of the dollar, and the passage of the International Banking Act of 1978. The Japanese banking presence was found to be positively related to Japanese foreign direct investment in the U.S. and the Japanese Banking Act of 1982, and inversely related to the yen/$ exchange rate.
